=9100RVDW.txt  aC0bGPO  aHistoric Shelflist; Drawer 302; LAC56  aHistoric Shelflist Drawer 302; HSL003; 2026020403698cam a2200565 a 00079479420260204162552.0100920s1973    dcuad    bt  f000 0 eng d  a(OCoLC)664572793  aEJBbengcEJBdOCLCQdOCLCFdOCLCAdOCLCQdIQUdEJBdELBdOCLCAdOCLCOdOCLCLdOCLCQdOCLCLdGPO  aa-ja---  aGPOO0 aEP 1.23/2:73-284  aEPA/R2-73-2841 aAndō, Junpei,d1925-2012.1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCjKryP4FGRT6FHCrgcjBfq10aNitrogen oxide abatement technology in Japan, 1973 /cby Jumpei Ando and Heiichiro Tohata ; prepared for Office of Research and Monitoring, U.S. Environmental Protection Agency.3 aNOx abatement technology in Japan (May 1973)  a[Washington, D.C.] :b[U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, Office of Research and Monitoring],c1973.  aiv, 37 leaves :billustrations, charts ;c28 cm.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  aunmediatedbn2rdamedia  avolumebnc2rdacarrier1 aEnvironmental Protection Service series  aAUG 16 1973.  a"June 1973."  a"EPA/R2-73-284."  a"EPA Task Officer: Frank T. Princiotta."  aFinal.  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP); no FDLP item number.  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds  aSponsored by EPA, Office of Research and Developmentb68-02-0242e1A2013g113 a"The report documents development, demonstration, and control now in progress in Japan on Japanese processes pertaining to NOx abatement from flue gases. It includes Japanese environmental emission and control standards, and measurement methods. It presents process descriptions, states of development, advantages, disadvantages, economics, and flow sheets for 13 processes (including combustion control, reduction, and adsorption) for NOx abatement from waste gases. A new type of burner seems most promising for combustion modification; catalytic reduction seems most promising for NOx removal from flue gases. NOx source contributions in the Tokyo Bay area are: 39% motor vehicles, 22% electricity generation, 31% industry, and 8% other sources."--Abstract.  aIncludes bibliographical references (leaf 37). 0aAtmospheric nitrogen oxideszJapan. 0aFlue gasesxPurificationxEquipment and supplies. 0aAir qualityxStandardszJapan. 0aAirxPollutionxStandardszJapan. 7aAirxPollutionxStandards.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00802166 7aAir qualityxStandards.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00802527 7aAtmospheric nitrogen oxides.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00820447 7aFlue gasesxPurificationxEquipment and supplies.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00927944 7aJapan.2fast0(OCoLC)fst012040821https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PBJkT7GyCmyjxytDfqk6Yfq1 aTohata, Heiichiro.1 aPrinciotta, Frank T.1 aUnited States.bEnvironmental Protection Agency.bOffice of Research and Monitoring.  ihas work:aNitrogen oxide abatement technology in Japan, 1973 (Text)1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCFPDXmPW48ddK4WqjRm8834https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/ontology/hasWork 0aEnvironmental Protection Service report series.  aC0bGPO  aHistoric Shelflist; Drawer 302; LAC56  aHistoric Shelflist Drawer 312; HSL003; 2026020402659cam a2200529 i 00079482220260204163051.0740408s1973    dcua     bt  f000 0 eng d  a(OCoLC)851674  aUDIbengerdacUDIdCWRdOCLdLHLdMTGdTXJdFUGdOCLCQdOCLCAdOCLCFdOCLCQdUAFdVA@dOCLCQdEJBdOCLCQdEJBdAGLdOCLCOdTRAALdOCLCOdOCLCQdOCLCLdGPO  aGPOO14aTD172b.E46 no.287  aTD172.E57 No.73-287  a0431-I-120 aEP 1.23/2:73-2870 aEP 1.23/2:R 2-73-287  aEPA R2-73-2871 aTuwiner, Sidney B.q(Sidney Bertram),d1912-eauthor.10aInvestigation of treating electroplaters cyanide waste by electrodialysis /cby Sidney B. Tuwiner. 1aWashington, D.C. :bU.S. G.P.O.,c1973.  avii, 48 pages :billustrations ;c27 cm.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  aunmediatedbn2rdamedia  avolumebnc2rdaca