.  avii, 75 pages :billustrations ;c28 cm.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  aunmediatedbn2rdamedia  avolumebnc2rdacarrier1 aEnvironmental Protection Technology ;vEPA-R2-73-288  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP); no FDLP item number.  aSEP 20 1973.  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds  aPrepared as an in-house report, Work Unit no. 21, ADJ 51.  a4to. 0aAirxPollution. 0aFilters and filtration. 7aAirxPollution.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00802083 7aFilters and filtration.2fast0(OCoLC)fst009243282 aNational Environmental Research Center (Research Triangle Park, N.C.).bControl Systems Laboratory. 0aResearch reporting series.n2,pEnvironmental protection technology ;vEPA-R2-73-288.  aC0bGPO  aHistoric Shelflist Drawer 302; HSL003; 20260204  aHistoric Shelflist; Drawer 302; LAC5603783cam a2200553 i 00079483720260204171050.0740410s1973    dcua     bt  f000 0 eng d  a(OCoLC)853423  aUDIbengerdacUDIdOCLdOCLCQdLHLdTXJdFUGdOCLCQdOCLCAdOCLCFdOCLCQdEJBdFTUdTXIdUAFdVA@dOCLCQdAGLdOCLCOdTRAALdOCLCOdOCLCQdGPO  aGPOO14aQH541b.R2 EPA-, R2-, 73-289  a0431-I-120 aEP 1.23/2:73-2890 aEP 1.23/2:R 2-73-289  aEPA-R2-73-2891 aRudder, C. L.,eauthor.10aAerial detection of spill sources /cby C.L. Rudder, A.G. Wallace [and] C.J. Reinheimer. 1aWashington, D.C. :b[U.S. G.P.O.],c1973.  avi, 23 pages :billustrations ;c27 cm.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  aunmediatedbn2rdamedia  avolumebnc2rdacarrier1 aEnvironmental protection technology series ;v289  aMAY 20 1974.  aProvisional headings on card verso.  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP).  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds.  a"Prepared for Office of Research and Development, U.S. Environmental Protection Agency under contract 68-01-01-0178, program element 1BB041."  aIncludes bibliographical references (page 23).0 aConclusions -- Recommendations -- Introduction -- Experimental program -- Data analysis -- Discussion.  aA unique interpretation key emphasizing the environmental aspects of the petroleum industry was developed as an integral part of an aerial surveillance spill prevention system. The petroleum refinery key is a unique collection of aerial and ground photographs and textual information organized to expedite the location and identification of spill threats through the use of conventional and aerial multiband photographs. The addition of aerial multiband photographs, spill threat analyses, spectral and chemical analyses of spilled materials distinguish this key from standard military interpretation keys. Throughout the aerial spill detection key, the material descriptively related oil refinery features to potential contamination of natural water resources. In addition to serving as a reference manual for imagery interpreters, they key can aid in training imagery interpreters to recognize refinery facilities, equipment, processes and associated spill threats. The key, while prepared for petroleum refineries, can serve as a model for other industries for which imagery interpretation keys are desired.  b68-01-01-0178e1BB041 0aPetroleum refineries. 0aPhotographic interpretation. 0aAerial photography. 7arefineries.2aat0(CStmoGRI)aat300006254 7aaerial photography.2aat0(CStmoGRI)aat300053443 7aAerial photography2fast0(OCoLC)fst00798078 7aPetroleum refineries2fast0(OCoLC)fst01059789 7aPhotographic interpretation2fast0(OCoLC)fst010616551 aWallace, A. G.,eauthor.1 aReinheimer, C. J.,eauthor.1 aUnited States.bEnvironmental Protection Agency.bOffice of Research and Development,eissuing body.08iOnline version:aRudder, C. L.tAerial detection of spill sourcesw(OCoLC)1401096603 0aResearch reporting series.n2,pEnvironmental protection technology ;v73-289.  aC0bGPO  aHistoric Shelflist; Drawer 302; LAC56  aHistoric Shelflist Drawer 302; HSL003; 2026020402316cam a2200517 a 00079485420260204172105.0010622s1973    dcua     bt  f000 0 eng d  a(OCoLC)47177552  aEKBbengcEKBdOCLCQdWPGdOCLCFdOCLCQdOCLCOdIQUdEJBdELBdOCLCQdOCLCOdOCLdOCLCOdGPO  aGPOO0 aEP 1.23/2:73-2910 aEP 1.23/2:72-291  aEPA/R2-73-2911 aBowman, C. T.10aNitric oxide formation in combustion processes with strong recirculation /cby C.T. Bowman, L.S. Cohen, and M.N. Director.  aWashington, D.C. :bU.S. Environmental Protection Agency, Office of Research and Monitorng,c[1973]  axi, 134 pages :billustrations ;c28 cm.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  aunmediatedbn2rdamedia  avolumebnc2rdacarrier1 aEnvironmental protection technology series  aSEP 20 1973.  aEPA project officer: G.B. Martin.  aPrepared by United Aircraft Research Laboratories.b68-02-0252e1A2014  a"July 1973."  aFinal report.  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 105-108).  a"EPA/R2-73-291."  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP).  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds. 0aCombustion gases. 0aNitric oxide. 0aFlue gases. 7aFlue gases2fast0(OCoLC)fst00927924 7aCombustion gases2fast0(OCoLC)fst00869057 7aNitric oxide2fast0(OCoLC)fst010379841 aCohen, L. S.1 aDirector, M. N.1 aMartin, G. Blair.1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCjFXcW6DGJQM47FFrcPJ6q2 aUnited Aircraft Corporation.bResearch Laboratories.1 aUnited States.bEnvironmental Protection Agency.bOffice of Research and Monitoring. 0aResearch reporting series.n2,pEnvironmental protection technology.  aC0bGPO  aHistoric Shelflist; Drawer 302; LA